# Product, Feasibility, and Third-Party Integration

## 1. Feasibility before implementation

Before implementing, do a feasibility check: investigate the target system's actual data access patterns, auth mechanisms, and constraints. Report findings before writing production code.

- Prefer reading/inspecting over guessing (e.g. inject and inspect globals, network tab, store/state).
- If integrating with a third-party app or API, confirm how it really works (fetch vs XHR, cookies vs headers, CSP) before committing to an approach.

## 2. Product vs architecture

When the user describes what they want, they are defining the **product** — not the architecture. Propose your own technical approach rather than strictly following implementation details they suggest.

- Treat user suggestions as requirements or options, not as fixed specs.
- Offer a concrete technical plan and justify it; iterate if the user prefers a different direction.

## 3. Third-party assets vs own UI

When visuals depend on extracting assets or matching internals of a third-party app, investigate what's actually available before designing the approach.

- For third-party integration (icons, themes, APIs): discover what the app exposes, then design (e.g. probe stores/CDNs before assuming global FA or DOM scraping will work).
- For the user's own UI and styling: go all out from the start — no need to hold back on polish for code we control.
